Not a very good article. I don't know if it came from a confused doctor
or a confused reporter.

It implies that T1 is defined mostly as &quot;insulin-dependent&quot; and that any T2
who becomes insulin-dependent might be T1 also.

In fact, all T2 will become insulin-dependent if they live long enough.
Work your program and you might hold it off until age 115. Ignore the
standard delaying therapy and you could be using insulin at age 15:

a. Lose fat lb
b. Gain muscle lb
c. Exercise every day
d. Ration your carb

I have read newspaper profiles of some of these 15-year old &quot;double
diabetics&quot;. IMO, they are cursed with ample supplies of the Type 2
Diabetes genes and the Insulin Resistance genes. However, their
lifestyles:

a. Gain fat lb, starting very young
b. Forget about muscle
c. No exercise, never
d. Carb, carb, carb

don't help one bit.

Something to think about: My T2 gene-laden daughter-in-law takes her
kindergarden son jogging with her (he rides his bike). My T2 gene-laden
neighbor takes her teen and pre-teen children on 30-mile bike rides.

