"/> The debate hinges on the definition of &quot;insufficient insulin&quot; If you
need 50 units to process a meal and can only come up with 49 units, you
have &quot;insufficient insulin&quot; even though a non-diabetic or normal person
might only need 8 units to process that same meal. IOW, you could be
making six times as much insulin as a normal person at that time, but you
would still have &quot;insufficient insulin&quot;.

Non-diabetics have 2-4 times as much insulin capacity as they need. Making
a normal amount of insulin is still consistent with &quot;about 50% of their beta
cells destroyed at the time of first diagnosis&quot;.

Write a definition of &quot;sufficient and insufficient&quot; which is tied to
&quot;amounts normally generated by non-diabetics and suddenly a lots of T2 have
&quot;sufficient&quot; insulin.

Write a definition of &quot;sufficient and insufficient&quot; which is tied to &quot;do you
have enough to process normal meals&quot; and suddenly lots of T2 have
&quot;insufficient&quot; insulin.

I agree with the latter approach to writing the definition because of my
reading of Dr. Hayden's papers and Slide 10 in the speech at
http://www.medscape.com/viewprogram/145 , i.e. the UKPDS established the
50% destruction at time of first diagnosis.

If we had a &quot;Lord High Doctor Czar of Diabetes&quot; to establish the
definitions, everybody would use the same terms in the same ways and these
discussions would be moot.

I lifted the &quot;overwhelming majority of Type 2 Diabetes have high Insulin
Resistance&quot; quote from a medical site. I prefer that approach since a
single instance of a T2 without high Insulin Resistance disproves the &quot;all&quot;
statement. If you write the definition based on the cause of beta cell
death you have a more clear cut separation between Type 1 and Type 2,
i.e. IAPP induced Apoptosis vs auto-immune episodes.

High Insulin Resistance is an extremely common co-factor perhaps the
universal co-factor; probably the underlying cause of all T2 in that it
accelerates the beta death rate so that &quot;insufficient insulin&quot; shows up
before the T2 dies of old age. Writing the definition based on the
mechanism of beta cell death is cleaner.

